[2]
Date: 27 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CBC News
<http://www.cbc.ca/stories/2004/03/27/canada/avianflu040327>


B.C. worker had mild form of avian flu
-------------------------
A person who handled dead chickens on a Fraser Valley farm contracted the
avian flu virus, the B.C. provincial health officer has confirmed.

Dr. Perry Kendall says it may be the first time the virus has been detected
in humans in Canada.

Health officials say it was the H7 variety of the flu, and not the same
strain [that was responsible for human deaths in] southeast Asia. [The H5N1
strain is the strain associated with human deaths in southeast Asia. The
H7N3 strain is the strain involved in the current outbreak in British
Columbia Canada. - Mod.MPP] Kendall says the H7 virus is not believed to
pose any serious risk to humans.

The man in question was working for the Canadian Food Inspection Agency. He
developed conjunctivitis, or pink eye, as a result of the virus, but
quickly recovered.

Several others who had contact with dead chickens after visiting
quarantined Matsqui-area poultry barns are being checked for avian flu.

Dr. Andrew Larder says 10 other workers have developed cold-like symptoms.
He says five have been tested so far, and health officials have determined
that none had avian flu.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In 2003 an outbreak of avian influenza A (H7N7) virus in poultry in The
Netherlands was accompanied by about 80 cases of human infection among
workers carrying out the cull and the death of one veterinarian, possible
from an unrelated cause. The disease symptoms were mild and conjunctivitis
was common, possibly because the eye is a portal of entry for most
respiratory viruses. There was no evidence of person-to-person
transmission. The infection of the Canadian worker is the first report of
human infection by an avian influenza A (H7N3) virus. It is becoming
increasingly clear that individuals exposed to large amounts of avian
influenza viruses by the nature of their occupation are at risk of
infection. So far there has been no evidence of person-to-person
transmission of infection, but there is clearly a need for implementation
of stricter protective measures. - Mod.CP]
